<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="426106c9-dadd-5b70-a628-88ce49cb0d44" activityNameId="d65f18e7-9024-4bc8-8f29-83087a405998" parentActivityId="71f59e74-b2cc-4f7f-a48b-ef9397415eda" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1" energyValues="0">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">cyanoacetic acid production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">C3H3NO2</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en"/>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">production of cyanoacetic acid including materials, energy uses, infrastructure, and emissions</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The process “cyanoacetic acid, at plant, GLO" is modelled for the production of cyanoacetic acid from chloroacetic acid. Raw materials are modelled with a stoechiometric calculation. Emissions are estimated. Energy consumptions, infrastructure and transports are calculated with standard values.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Cyanoacetic acid (C3H3NO2; CAS 372-09-8) forms colourless, hygroscopic crystals, that undergo decarboxylation above 160 °C to give acetonitrile. The compound has a dissociation constant of 3.65 × 10–3 in water (25 °C) and dissolves readily in water, but is only moderately soluble in ethanol, and sparingly in benzene. The industrially most important cyanoacetate is ethyl cyanoacetate, followed by the methyl ester. Both esters are colourless liquids, which are miscible with ethanol and diethyl ether but insoluble in water. Cyanoacetic acid and the cyanoacetates are produced by the same route (and often in the same plant) as the malonates by cyanidation of sodium chloroacetate followed by acidification of the sodium cyanoacetate solution. Cyanoacetic acid is isolated by extraction with an organic solvent and evaporation of the solvent, whereas the cyanoacetates are obtained by mineral acid-catalyzed esterification with subsequent azeotropic removal of water. Major byproducts are malonates and succinates. A process variation involves interchange of the cyanidation and esterification steps. In this case, however, the formation of the side product dimethyl or diethyl 2-cyanosuccinate is difficult to suppress. In order to avoid the isolation, most of the cyanoacetic acid outlets are produced directly from solution.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The world's largest cyanoacetate plant was brought on stream in 1987 in Mobile (Alabama) by Hüls. The annual production capacity of this plant was later expanded to 8000 t.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Alternative methods for the preparation of cyanoacetic acid involve the carboxylation of acetonitrile and the oxidation of partially oxidized propionitriles. Other methods for the preparation of cyanoacetates include the cleavage of cyanoacetaldehyde dimethyl acetal, formed by a palladium-catalyzed oxidation of acrylonitrile, the alkoxycarbonylation of chloroacetonitrile and pyrolysis of 3,3′-bisisoxazole in the presence of an alcohol. However, none of these processes have been used industrially.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">The most important application of cyanoacetates is in the field of adhesives. Knoevenagel reaction of alkyl cyanoacetates with formaldehyde affords α-cyanoacrylates, which are stable under exclusion of air but polymerize rapidly to polycyanoacrylates after application on a surface even at room temperature. This polymerization is reversible on heating and the monomer can be formed back and subsequently polymerized again by traces of moisture. Esters of higher alcohols, such as 1-butanol, are also employed.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Otherwise, cyanoacetates are used for the synthesis of pharmaceuticals, agrochemicals, dyes, and UV absorbers. For many applications cyanoacetic acid, cyanoacetates, or cyanoacetamide can be used alternatively. Caffeine (R = CH3) is synthesized from theophylline (R = H), which is accessible in several steps from cyanoacetic acid and 1,3-dimethylurea. The traded cyanoacetic acid is mainly used for the production of the fungicide cymoxanil and the cough remedy dextromethorphan.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Frischknecht R., Jungbluth N., Althaus H.-J., Doka G., Dones R., Heck T., Hellweg S., Hischier R., Nemecek T., Rebitzer G. and Spielmann M. (2007) Overview and Methodology. Final report ecoinvent v2.0 No. 1. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH, retrieved from: www.ecoinvent.org.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Gendorf (2000) Umwelterklärung 2000, Werk Gendorf. Werk Gendorf, Burgkirchen as pdf-File under: http://www.gendorf.de/pdf/umwelterklaerung2000.pdf</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">Kim 2003: Kim S., Overcash M.: Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate-to-gate information for life cycle as-sessment. In: Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology vol. 78,  no. 9: 995-1005(11). 2003</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="13"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="14">Harald Strittmatter, Stefan Hildbrand, Peter Pollak: Malonic Acid and Derivatives. Published online: 2007. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: DOI: 10.1002/14356007.a16_063.pub2</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
